<!--
	Guided Lecture Notes worksheet: "Homogeneous Linear Equations
	(constant coefficients)"
	Book sections (Exploring Differential Equations, geoff-cox/debookrs):
		c8-lhcc/sec-lhcc-eqn.ptx
		c8-lhcc/sec-exponential-solns.ptx
		c8-lhcc/sec-second-order-lhcc-eqns.ptx
		c8-lhcc/sec-higher-order-lhcc-eqns.ptx
		c8-lhcc/sec-solving-higher-order-lhcc-eqns.ptx
	Old deck: source/notes/latex/ folder "04 lhcc".
	Previous worksheet: ws-eulers-method.ptx; next: ws-undetermined-coefficients.

	Per the sourcing rules, every equation here is fresh: concepts mirror
	the book, but none of the example equations appear in it (nor in the
	old deck or the earlier worksheets). Per the instructor overrides in
	CLAUDE.md section 4: no interactive content, and the whole topic stays
	on this one worksheet.

	Worksheet conventions: checklists/worksheet-conventions.md (see
	CLAUDE.md section 4 for this repo's parameters). In brief:
	  * Student/instructor split via component="stu" / component="key",
	    mirrored in structure; answers never live inside <fillin>.
	  * Worked problems: paired <exercise component="stu" workspace="Xin">
	    and <exercise component="key"> (statement + solution).
	  * True/False checks: one <exercise> + <solution component="key">.
	  * <page> = vertical print space, not topics; headings are
	    <p><term>...</term></p>; display math uses <md> (<me>/<men> are
	    prohibited here).
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-homogeneous-linear" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Homogeneous Linear Equations with Constant Coefficients</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li><p><term>Identify</term> LHCC equations: linear, homogeneous (zero forcing function), constant coefficients.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Explain</term> why exponentials <m>e^{rx}</m> are the natural candidates, and derive the characteristic equation by substitution.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Solve</term> second-order LHCC equations in all three cases&#8212;distinct real, complex, and repeated roots.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Apply</term> two initial conditions to pin down both constants in an IVP.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Extend</term> the method to higher-order equations via factored characteristic polynomials.</p></li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 1 : What counts as LHCC                                          -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>A new family: second order and beyond.</term></p>

		<p>
			Every technique so far handled <em>first-order</em> equations. We now
			jump to a family where exact solutions exist at any order:
			<term>linear homogeneous constant coefficient</term> (LHCC) equations,
			such as <m>a\,y'' + b\,y' + c\,y = 0</m>. Each word earns its place:
			<em>linear</em> (no powers or products of <m>y</m> and its
			derivatives), <em>homogeneous</em> (the forcing function&#8212;the
			free term&#8212;is zero), and <em>constant coefficients</em> (the
			multipliers <m>a, b, c</m> are numbers, not functions of <m>x</m>).
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						In this setting the free term is renamed the
						<fillin characters="16"/>; an equation is <term>homogeneous</term>
						when that term equals <fillin characters="4"/>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						In this setting the free term is renamed the
						<m>\underline{\textbf{forcing function}}</m>; an equation is
						<term>homogeneous</term> when that term equals
						<m>\underline{\textbf{zero}}</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						An LHCC equation has <term>constant coefficients</term>: every
						coefficient is a constant rather than a function of the
						<fillin characters="11"/> variable.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						An LHCC equation has <term>constant coefficients</term>: every
						coefficient is a constant rather than a function of the
						<m>\underline{\textbf{independent}}</m> variable.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-tf-varcoeff">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p><m>y'' + (\cos x)\,y' + 2y = 0</m> is an LHCC equation.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False. It is linear and homogeneous, but the coefficient
					<m>\cos x</m> is a function of <m>x</m>, not a constant. The
					characteristic-equation machinery we are about to build depends on
					<em>all three</em> letters of LHCC.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-ex-identify" component="stu" workspace="2.2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For each equation, decide whether it is LHCC. If not, name the
					property that fails.
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ y'' - 5y' + 4y = 0 \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ y'' + 2y' = 7 </mrow>
						<mrow> \text{(c)}\ y'' + (y')^2 = 0 \qquad
						       \text{(d)}\ y''' + 2y'' - y = 0 </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-ex-identify" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For each equation, decide whether it is LHCC. If not, name the
					property that fails.
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ y'' - 5y' + 4y = 0 \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ y'' + 2y' = 7 </mrow>
						<mrow> \text{(c)}\ y'' + (y')^2 = 0 \qquad
						       \text{(d)}\ y''' + 2y'' - y = 0 </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) LHCC: linear, forcing function <m>0</m>, coefficients
					<m>1, -5, 4</m> all constant.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) Not homogeneous: the forcing function is <m>7</m>, not zero.
					(Equations like this are next worksheet's business.)
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) Not linear: <m>(y')^2</m> raises a derivative to a power.
				</p>
				<p>
					(d) LHCC&#8212;order three is welcome; nothing in the definition
					stops at second order.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 2 : Why exponentials; the characteristic equation               -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Why exponentials? The like-terms argument.</term></p>

		<p>
			For <m>a\,y'' + b\,y' + c\,y</m> to collapse to zero, the three terms
			must be <em>like-terms</em>&#8212;they must cancel by addition. That
			demands a function whose derivatives are like-terms with itself, and
			the exponential <m>y = e^{rx}</m> is the function built for the job:
			every derivative is just a constant multiple of <m>e^{rx}</m>.
			Substituting it turns the differential equation into algebra.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						Substituting <m>y = e^{rx}</m> into an LHCC equation and factoring
						out <m>e^{rx}</m> leaves a polynomial in <m>r</m> called the
						<fillin characters="14"/> equation. Each root <m>r</m> produces a
						<fillin characters="11"/> solution <m>e^{rx}</m>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						Substituting <m>y = e^{rx}</m> into an LHCC equation and factoring
						out <m>e^{rx}</m> leaves a polynomial in <m>r</m> called the
						<m>\underline{\textbf{characteristic}}</m> equation. Each root
						<m>r</m> produces a <m>\underline{\textbf{fundamental}}</m>
						solution <m>e^{rx}</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-tf-nonzero">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>The step from <m>(a r^2 + b r + c)\,e^{rx} = 0</m> to <m>a r^2 + b r + c = 0</m> is valid because <m>e^{rx}</m> is never zero.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					True. An exponential <m>e^{rx}</m> is strictly positive for every
					real <m>x</m>, so the product can vanish only if the polynomial
					factor does. That harmless-looking division is what converts
					calculus into algebra.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-ex-ansatz" component="stu" workspace="2.8in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Substitute <m>y = e^{rx}</m> into
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' + y' - 6y = 0, </mrow>
					</md>
					factor out <m>e^{rx}</m>, and solve the resulting characteristic
					equation. Then write the two fundamental solutions and the general
					solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-ex-ansatz" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Substitute <m>y = e^{rx}</m> into
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' + y' - 6y = 0, </mrow>
					</md>
					factor out <m>e^{rx}</m>, and solve the resulting characteristic
					equation. Then write the two fundamental solutions and the general
					solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					With <m>y = e^{rx}</m>, <m>y' = r e^{rx}</m> and
					<m>y'' = r^2 e^{rx}</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> r^2 e^{rx} + r e^{rx} - 6 e^{rx} \amp = 0 </mrow>
						<mrow> \left(r^2 + r - 6\right) e^{rx} \amp = 0. </mrow>
					</md>
					Since <m>e^{rx} \neq 0</m>, the characteristic equation is
					<m>r^2 + r - 6 = (r+3)(r-2) = 0</m>, with roots <m>r = -3</m> and
					<m>r = 2</m>. The fundamental solutions are <m>e^{-3x}</m> and
					<m>e^{2x}</m>, and superposition assembles the general solution:
					<md>
						<mrow> y = c_1 e^{-3x} + c_2 e^{2x}. </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 3 : The three cases at second order                              -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Three kinds of roots, three solution forms.</term></p>

		<p>
			The quadratic <m>a r^2 + b r + c = 0</m> can behave three ways,
			sorted by the discriminant <m>\Delta = b^2 - 4ac</m>&#8212;and each
			way dictates the shape of the general solution.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						<term>Case 1</term> (<m>\Delta &gt; 0</m>), unequal real roots:
						<m>y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}</m>.
						<term>Case 2</term> (<m>\Delta &lt; 0</m>), complex roots
						<m>r = \alpha \pm i\beta</m>:
						<m>y = e^{\alpha x}\left(c_1 \cos(\beta x) + c_2 \sin(\beta x)\right)</m>,
						where the sine and cosine come from <fillin characters="7"/>
						formula. <term>Case 3</term> (<m>\Delta = 0</m>), a repeated
						root: the second fundamental solution gains an extra factor of
						<fillin characters="3"/>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						<term>Case 1</term> (<m>\Delta &gt; 0</m>), unequal real roots:
						<m>y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}</m>.
						<term>Case 2</term> (<m>\Delta &lt; 0</m>), complex roots
						<m>r = \alpha \pm i\beta</m>:
						<m>y = e^{\alpha x}\left(c_1 \cos(\beta x) + c_2 \sin(\beta x)\right)</m>,
						where the sine and cosine come from
						<m>\underline{\textbf{Euler's}}</m> formula.
						<term>Case 3</term> (<m>\Delta = 0</m>), a repeated root: the
						second fundamental solution gains an extra factor of
						<m>\underline{\textbf{x}}</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-ex-cases" component="stu" workspace="3.4in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solution of each equation, and say which case it
					falls in.
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ y'' - 10y' + 25y = 0 \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ y'' + 6y' + 13y = 0 \qquad
						       \text{(c)}\ y'' + 9y = 0 </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-ex-cases" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solution of each equation, and say which case it
					falls in.
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ y'' - 10y' + 25y = 0 \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ y'' + 6y' + 13y = 0 \qquad
						       \text{(c)}\ y'' + 9y = 0 </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) <m>r^2 - 10r + 25 = (r - 5)^2 = 0</m>: repeated root
					<m>r = 5</m> (Case 3), so
					<md>
						<mrow> y = c_1 e^{5x} + c_2\,x\,e^{5x}. </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) <m>r^2 + 6r + 13 = 0</m> gives
					<m>r = \frac{-6 \pm \sqrt{36 - 52}}{2} = -3 \pm 2i</m> (Case 2,
					<m>\alpha = -3</m>, <m>\beta = 2</m>):
					<md>
						<mrow> y = e^{-3x}\left(c_1 \cos(2x) + c_2 \sin(2x)\right). </mrow>
					</md>
					A decaying envelope times an oscillation.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) <m>r^2 + 9 = 0</m> gives <m>r = \pm 3i</m>&#8212;Case 2 with
					<m>\alpha = 0</m>, so the exponential envelope is
					<m>e^{0x} = 1</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> y = c_1 \cos(3x) + c_2 \sin(3x), </mrow>
					</md>
					pure oscillation that never grows or decays.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-tf-repeated">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>If the characteristic equation has the repeated root <m>r</m>, then <m>y = c_1 e^{rx} + c_2 e^{rx}</m> is the general solution.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False. Those two terms are like-terms, so the sum collapses to
					<m>(c_1 + c_2)e^{rx}</m>&#8212;one arbitrary constant masquerading
					as two, which cannot meet two independent initial conditions. The
					genuine second solution is <m>x\,e^{rx}</m>, giving
					<m>y = c_1 e^{rx} + c_2\,x\,e^{rx}</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 4 : IVPs; higher order; looking ahead                            -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Pinning down the constants, and going higher.</term></p>

		<p>
			A second-order general solution carries <em>two</em> arbitrary
			constants, so an initial-value problem must supply <em>two</em>
			conditions&#8212;typically <m>y(0)</m> and <m>y'(0)</m>. And the
			characteristic-equation method scales: an order-<m>n</m> LHCC
			equation yields a degree-<m>n</m> polynomial, and its <m>n</m> roots
			build the general solution the same way.
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-ex-ivp" component="stu" workspace="3.0in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve the initial-value problem
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' + y' - 6y = 0, \qquad y(0) = 1, \qquad y'(0) = -8. </mrow>
					</md>
					(The general solution comes from page 2.)
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-ex-ivp" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve the initial-value problem
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' + y' - 6y = 0, \qquad y(0) = 1, \qquad y'(0) = -8. </mrow>
					</md>
					(The general solution comes from page 2.)
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					From page 2, <m>y = c_1 e^{-3x} + c_2 e^{2x}</m>, so
					<m>y' = -3c_1 e^{-3x} + 2c_2 e^{2x}</m>. The conditions give the
					system
					<md>
						<mrow> y(0) = c_1 + c_2 \amp = 1 </mrow>
						<mrow> y'(0) = -3c_1 + 2c_2 \amp = -8. </mrow>
					</md>
					Substituting <m>c_1 = 1 - c_2</m> into the second:
					<m>-3 + 5c_2 = -8</m>, so <m>c_2 = -1</m> and <m>c_1 = 2</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> y = 2e^{-3x} - e^{2x}. </mrow>
					</md>
					Two constants, two conditions, one solution&#8212;the second-order
					echo of <q>each constant needs its own condition</q> from direct
					integration.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-ex-higher" component="stu" workspace="2.6in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solution of the third-order equation
					<md>
						<mrow> y''' - 9y' = 0. </mrow>
					</md>
					(Factor the characteristic polynomial completely; one root is
					<m>0</m>.)
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-hl-ex-higher" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solution of the third-order equation
					<md>
						<mrow> y''' - 9y' = 0. </mrow>
					</md>
					(Factor the characteristic polynomial completely; one root is
					<m>0</m>.)
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The characteristic equation is
					<m>r^3 - 9r = r\,(r-3)(r+3) = 0</m>, with the three roots
					<m>r = 0, 3, -3</m>. Each contributes a fundamental solution&#8212;and
					<m>r = 0</m> contributes <m>e^{0x} = 1</m>, a constant:
					<md>
						<mrow> y = c_1 + c_2 e^{3x} + c_3 e^{-3x}. </mrow>
					</md>
					Order three, degree three, three roots, three constants: the
					bookkeeping scales perfectly.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<title>Looking ahead</title>
			<p>
				Homogeneous means nothing pushes on the system&#8212;the forcing
				function is zero. The next worksheet turns the forcing on:
				equations like <m>y'' + y' - 6y = f(x)</m> model driven springs and
				circuits, and the method of <em>undetermined coefficients</em>
				finds a particular solution to add to the homogeneous one we can
				now build.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>
</worksheet>
